"Follow your own heart, seize the opportunity, regardless of the consequences, sometimes there will be unexpected gains."
Although it was a graduation concert, many songs also moved non-graduates.
"The whole scene really wants to cry, whose youth is full of beauty and regret, but it is worth remembering, and we must bravely go on."
Beijing's natural ecology continues to improve, attracting more than 500 species of wild animals to "settle" in the city
2020-07-26 05:03:17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sisuo Editor: Wang Sisuo
The capital's natural ecology continues to improve, attracting wildlife to "settle" in the city
Beijing has more than 500 species of wild animals
Our reporter (reporter Wang Bin) learned from the Beijing Youth Daily that in recent years, as the capital's natural ecological environment has continued to improve, the types and numbers of wild animals have also continued to increase.
At present, the terrestrial vertebrate wildlife inhabiting Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including national first-class protected animals such as brown horse chicken and black stork, as well as national second-class protected animals such as gazelle, swan, gray crane and stork.
Whether it is an urban forest planted in the Second Ring Road or a small wetland embedded between buildings, it not only brings the wildness of nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to "settle" in the city.
In midsummer, the Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is full of life.
A toad was playing leisurely by the hillside, while two dog toads were fighting with each other.
Hu Qiaoli, director of the Songshan National Nature Reserve Management Office, said that by the end of 2019, there were 178 species of wild animals living in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares, including the national first-level protected animal golden eagle and the national second-level protected animal spoon chicken and zebra antelope. Nearly one-third of the city's wildlife species can be seen here.
"In Matsuyama, wild animals are the real 'masters', and our staff can only be regarded as 'bodyguards' at best."
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the situation of wild animals and plants in the protected area on the ground, more than 30 professional patrol members patrol along 16 carefully formulated protection routes every day, and there will be a "big circle" every month, spending a whole day to walk almost the entire protected area.
"During the inspection, it is not only necessary to check the recording of biodiversity, but also to check the installation of artificial bird nests, the rescue of injured wildlife, the installation of field infrared cameras, etc."
Songshan National Nature Reserve has now installed more than 200 infrared cameras to record the living conditions of wild animals in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli introduced that as the biodiversity of the protected area has been enriched in recent years, more and more wild animals have appeared in the camera, leopard cats, baboons and piglets have become "resident guests," and the "appearance rate" of the national second-class protected animal, the impala, has become higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, director of the Wildlife and Wetland Protection Department of the Beijing Municipal Bureau of Landscaping, said that Beijing's terrestrial vertebrate wildlife has increased from 461 species in 1994 to more than 500 species now, and the species and number of wild animals in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years.
The appearance of wild animals in the city is becoming more and more common, which is closely related to the escalating greening of the capital city in recent years.
In particular, the new round of afforestation and greening construction of one million mu, which began in 2018, proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, enhance the ecological functions of woodland and green space, and highlight the concept of "near nature."
The plan strives to achieve interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green space, making it convenient for wild animals to "visit relatives and friends," and the trees planted are also the favorite nectar and food plants of the animals.
Black soil "seeds" agricultural modernization - Xinhua
Xinhua News Agency, Harbin, July 26: Black soil "seeds" the modernization of agriculture
In midsummer, two spraying aircraft flew over the 10,000-acre high-yield demonstration field of the second operation station of the fifth management area of Friendship Farm, forming two white lines, and the words "the world's first field" planted with black rice seedlings in the green field were particularly striking.
Kong Lingqiang, director of the operation station, said that the aircraft can spray chemicals on more than 6,000 acres of cultivated land a day, which is about eight times more efficient than drones and hundreds of times more efficient than manual spraying.
This farm is located in Friendship County, Heilongjiang Province, the largest grain-producing province in China. Traditional Chinese farming and farms have been transformed in this black soil belt, from the sound of rice cutting in the past to the sound of motors today.
In addition to aircraft, satellites are also used in the modern agricultural production of Friendship Farms.
Kong Lingqiang said that on the one hand, they use satellite remote sensing technology to achieve precise fertilization, reduce agricultural input, and reduce pollution; on the other hand, satellite navigation technology can improve the level of standardized operation of agricultural machinery in the field.
In this year's rice production process, the farm expanded the operation area of satellite navigation unmanned planting technology from 3,000 mu last year to 30,000 mu.
This technology makes the planting of seedlings more uniform, maximizes the use of sunlight and cultivated land resources, and saves 16 yuan per acre in labor costs.
Farms have tried new technologies such as information and intelligence in agricultural production, forming the largest agricultural machinery group in China from the ground to the sky.
According to statistics, the total number of agricultural machinery on farms is 49,000 (pieces), and the comprehensive mechanization rate in the field is 99.8%.
Agricultural machinery operations achieve 100% of GPS satellite navigation, 100% of precision seeding in dry fields, and 100% of high-horsepower locomotive operations in dry fields.
"Green agriculture, smart agriculture and digital agriculture are the pathfinding directions for agricultural modernization."
Liu Hualian, director of the Friendship Farm, said.
The key to agricultural modernization lies in scientific and technological progress.
In recent years, Heilongjiang farmers, represented by farms, have played an exemplary and leading role in the "aircraft carrier" of modern agriculture, and initially established a modern agricultural industry system dominated by large-scale planting, standardized production, and industrialized management.
In the outskirts of Friendship County, there is an agricultural machinery exposition park covering an area of 350,000 square meters.
More than 140 (pieces) of agricultural machinery introduced and used by Heilongjiang farmers over the years are exhibited here.
These agricultural machinery and farms have witnessed the development of China's agricultural modernization.
A small house for everyone — Anhui Hefei Jiangkouhe joint mass transfer direct hit - Xinhua
Xinhua News Agency, Hefei, July 26th, title: A small home for everyone — Anhui Hefei Jiangkouhe joint mass transfer direct hit
Xinhua reporters Chen Shangying, Wang Liwu and Liu Xiacun
At more than 4 p.m. on July 25, Fu Kunbao, wearing muddy rubber shoes, went back and forth from the front room to the back room with his wife, Zhou Yan, busy packing things.
"When I received the call from the village officials to transfer, I was still weeding in the field."
Fu Kunbao said that he has circulated more than 60 acres of land, planted rice, and is now growing well. "I also took medicine yesterday, and I haven't packed any tools yet."
Fu Kunbao pointed to the pesticide sprayer in the corner. "No one wants to be flooded at home. Let's give up our homes for everyone."
In order to cope with the continuous high water level pressure and possible heavy rainfall in Chaohu, Hefei City, Anhui Province, is preparing to open the Jiangkou River, where Fu Kunbao's home is located, to flood water storage on the 26th.
Jiangkouhe Lianyu is located in Feixi County, close to the Chaohu Dike.
Several thousand villagers in Yandian Township and Sanhe Township need to be relocated.
As of 16:00 on the 25th, the water level of Lake Chaohu, the fifth largest freshwater lake in China, remained at a high level of 13.2 meters, exceeding the guaranteed water level by 0.7 meters.
Fu Kunbao's kitchen was clean and tidy, with a pot of pumpkin soup on the table and eggs and some pickled vegetables in the refrigerator.
"I didn't expect to move, but the water in the Jiangkou River looks good at the moment."
Zhou Yan said that the home is a bungalow, and some large objects have not yet figured out where to put them.
"Pack up your valuables first. Large items such as refrigerators and televisions can be temporarily placed in the homes of neighbors or relatives on higher ground."
Wang Liwen, a village cadre, gave Fu Kunbao an idea.
Wang Lijian was responsible for the relocation and resettlement of 13 villagers, notifying each household and confirming each person's resettlement plan.
The nearest settlement to Fu Kunbao's home is Yandian Township's Su Elementary School, about 2 kilometers away.
In addition to large items, Fu Kunbao and his wife also have more than 1,000 kilograms of grain and some newly purchased furniture.
"The food is ready to be dragged to a relative's house, and the furniture cannot be moved."
The couple discussed and put a stool under the newly purchased bed and raised the bed by about half a meter.
At 6 p.m., Fu Kunbao began to use a tricycle to transport things to relatives, and Zhou Yan continued to clean up at home.
At 11 o'clock in the evening, the couple looked back and forth at home, pulled the electric gate, and prepared to go to the resettlement site.
"Let's hope the water recedes soon."
Fu Kunbao said.
At 9:30 a.m. on July 26, the reporter saw at the site of Jiangkouhe Lianyu that the local authorities had made all preparations before the flood.
