Church fire in Nantes, France: Parish volunteer admits arson
China News Service, July 26th According to foreign media reports, on July 18th, the famous St. Peter and St. Paul Cathedral, a religious and historical architectural treasure in Nantes, France, was severely damaged in a fire, and the grand organ was completely destroyed.
On the 26th local time, the Nantes prosecutor announced that a parish volunteer who was responsible for the protection work in the cathedral had been charged with "arson and destruction."
He has admitted that he lit the fire in the church.
According to the report, local prosecutor Senas said that the 39-year-old parish volunteer from Rwanda admitted that he lit three fires in the cathedral at night.
The man's lawyer said the arsonist now regrets doing it.
This person entered France a few years ago through the asylum route, was sheltered in the parish where the fire occurred, and was sheltered in the church.
The prosecution pointed out that recently, he tried to renew his visa and was communicating with the police station about it.
But the church said it still could not believe that this usually very kind, smiling, but not very talkative believer would destroy the church he loved so much.
On the day of the fire on July 18, the volunteer had already been questioned by the police because of illogical questions in the narrative, but he was later released.
The picture shows firefighters carrying out rescue at the scene.
On the evening of the 25th, due to the new evidence obtained by the professional engineers in the laboratory of the Paris Central Police Station, the person was summoned again.
This time, the man admitted to setting the fire.
According to reports, the suspect could face 10 years in prison and a fine of 150,000 euros if convicted of deliberate arson and destruction.
According to the report, the fire caused serious damage to the Cathedral of St. Pierre and St. Paul. The organ in the church was completely burned, and the stained glass window behind the organ was also severely damaged.
Brunet, the chief architect of France's historic preservation architecture, believes that the restoration of Nantes Cathedral will take at least three years.
Comprehensive News: US unilateralism undermines bilateral relations International public opinion supports China's countermeasures against the US - Xinhua
Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, July 26 (Xinhua) -- On the morning of July 24, China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs informed the U.S. Embassy in China that China has decided to revoke the establishment and operation license of the U.S. Consulate General in Chengdu and put forward specific requirements for the Consulate General to stop all operations and activities.
International public opinion believes that the unilateral measures taken by the United States have caused serious trouble to the relations between China and the United States, and that it is legitimate and necessary for China to respond to the unreasonable provocations of the United States and take countermeasures.
Andres Borquez, director of the China Research Center of the Institute of International Studies of the University of Chile, said that the unilateral measures of the United States have destroyed the bridge of understanding between the people of China and the United States and caused a crisis in the relationship between the two major powers.
China's notice to the United States to close its Consulate General in Chengdu is a countermeasure to the US unilateral measures and is in line with diplomatic practice.
Patricio Giusto, a professor at the Catholic University of Argentina and director of the Argentina-China Research Center, believes that China's decision is a legitimate and necessary countermeasure to previous provocations by the United States, and is not aimed at ordinary Americans.
The United States is trying to divert the attention of the American people by pressuring China to cover up its inadequate response to the new coronavirus epidemic.
Bambang Suryono, chairman of the Asian Innovation Research Center, an Indonesian think tank, said that the United States has adopted a provocative diplomatic posture, which has caused serious trouble to the relations between China and the United States, and the relations between the two countries are facing serious challenges.
China's notice to the United States to close its Consulate General in Chengdu is a normal countermeasure, in line with diplomatic practice, which not only reflects China's principled position of resolutely safeguarding its own interests, but also reflects the reasonableness and advantages of China's diplomacy.
Tanzanian commentator Francis Semwinza said that China's decision was a legitimate and necessary response to US provocations.
For Sino-US relations to return to normal, the US should take the initiative to improve relations with China and stop interfering in China's internal affairs.
The United States should focus on how to achieve a win-win situation with China economically and politically, and how to benefit the people of both countries and the entire international community.
Ali Yusuf, executive director of the Sudan-based Federation of Arab-Chinese Friendship Associations, said that the countermeasures China was forced to take were a legitimate and necessary response to the unreasonable actions of the United States, in line with international law and the basic norms of international relations, as well as diplomatic practice.
Earlier, the US side demanded the closure of the Chinese Consulate General in Houston, which seriously violated international law and the basic norms of international relations.
It is hoped that the US will revoke its previous decision and create the necessary conditions for the normalization of bilateral relations.
Singapore's Lianhe Zaobao published an editorial saying that the United States' larger strategic intention is to contain China and prevent China from continuing to rise.
In the face of the United States' step-by-step pressure, although China is very reluctant to see Sino-US relations continue to deteriorate, it has to take countermeasures.
