The case is currently under further investigation.
The relevant person in charge of the Guangdong Coast Guard Bureau said that in the future, it will continue to maintain a high-pressure situation, crack down on all kinds of smuggling and criminal activities at sea, and maintain good order in the waters under its jurisdiction.
Hurricane "Hannah" makes landfall in Texas, may cause river surges and flash floods - China News Service
China News Service, July 26th Comprehensive foreign media reported that at 5 p.m. local time on the 25th, Hurricane "Hannah" landed in Texas, the United States, which will bring strong storms and rain to Texas, river surges, and may also cause life-threatening flash floods.
The National Hurricane Center says Hurricane Hanna is expected to sweep through parts of southern and northeastern Texas with heavy rains that could cause some creeks to swell and life-threatening flash floods.
According to the report, the worst affected by Hurricane Hanna is the area south of Corpus Christi to the mouth of the Rio Grande River, and the Rio Grande Valley may experience widespread flash floods.
Texas Governor Abbott said on the 25th: “Any hurricane is a huge challenge.”
Thirty-two counties in the state are under a state of disaster emergency because of the hurricane.
Corpus Christi, a city of more than 320,000 people, has closed its libraries and museums as residents brace for the worst.
Abbott also said that the hurricane should not be allowed to bring more casualties to Texas at a time when the state is being hit hard by the new coronavirus epidemic.
According to reports, precipitation in southern Texas is expected to reach 6 to 12 inches overnight on the 26th, and 3 to 5 inches of rain will also fall in northern Texas and coastal Louisiana.
Due to global warming and other factors, Hanna formed earlier than previous Atlantic hurricane seasons.
Typically, the first hurricane in the Atlantic does not form until mid-August.
Poland to withdraw from European treaty on preventing violence against women
Poland will take steps next week to withdraw from a European treaty on preventing violence against women, the justice ministry said Saturday.
Poland's right-wing government cabinet said the treaty trampled on the rights of parents by requiring schools to teach students about gender issues.
Poland's Justice Minister Józef Piłsudski told a news conference that his ministry would submit a request to the Ministry of Labor and Family on Monday to begin the process of withdrawing from the treaty.
That treaty is also known as the Istanbul Convention.
"The treaty contains elements that we consider to be of a pernicious ideological nature," Joublot said.
Poland's ruling Law and Justice party and its coalition partners are closely allied with the Roman Catholic Church and promote a conservative social agenda.
Polish President Andrzej Duda made hostility to gay rights one of the main issues during his successful re-election campaign this month.
On Friday, thousands of Poles, mostly women, protested in Warsaw and other cities against withdrawing from the convention.
"The purpose of withdrawing from the treaty is to legalize domestic violence," Lempat, one of the protest organizers, said at a protest march in Warsaw.
Some protesters carried banners that read "PiS is hell for women."
Law and Justice has long complained about the Istanbul Convention.
Poland's previous centrist-led government ratified the convention in 2015.
The Law and Justice government says the treaty does not respect religion and requires liberal social policies to be taught in schools.
But so far the party has not decided to withdraw from the convention.
(According to Reuters)
