Engine may stall, FAA orders urgent inspection of 2,000 Boeing airliners - Xinhua
The US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft registered in the United States, because the corrosion of the air check valve of the above-mentioned passenger aircraft may cause the engine to stop in the air.
The FAA said it has so far received four reports of 737NG and 737Classic engines stalling in the air, prompting it to order emergency inspections of planes that have been parked for seven days or more and those that have flown fewer than 11 times since returning to service.
The FAA warned that if the Level 5 check valves on both engines of the airliner were corroded, they could become stuck in the open position, causing the airliner to completely lose power and be unable to restart the engines.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, the airline operator must replace this key component before the passenger aircraft is put into service again.
Boeing responded later in the day that the outbreak of the new crown epidemic has led to a decrease in travel demand, and many passenger aircraft have been mothballed or used less. "The check valve is more susceptible to corrosion."
Boeing also said that it has advised air operators to inspect the passenger aircraft involved in the directive, and if problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in the repair and replacement of check valves.
The Associated Press reported that the passenger aircraft of major US airline operators usually fly many times a day, but after the outbreak of the new crown epidemic, a large number of passenger aircraft were grounded; with the recent slow growth in passenger travel demand, some passenger aircraft were put back into operation.
The FAA did not release details of the four air-stop reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its passenger planes was flying from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, on July 15 when an engine suddenly stopped. The passenger plane eventually made a successful emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines says it has replaced the plane's engine and has inspected the engines of six planes in accordance with FAA directives.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that their passenger aircraft did not have engine stalls associated with air check valves.
Four American Airlines planes will be inspected, and 28 United Airlines planes will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect 20 of its planes, but did not say whether there had been any engine shutdowns.
According to multiple media reports, the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive is another blow to Boeing.
A Boeing 737 MAX aircraft of Indonesia's Lion Air and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019, respectively, killing 346 people in total.
This series of airliners was subsequently grounded worldwide, and production was suspended in January this year and resumed in May.
FAA Administrator Steve Dickson admitted in June that the FAA had "made mistakes" in its oversight of Boeing over the 737 MAX.
