Cocos (Keeling) Islands Tibetan antelope enters migration season - Xinhua
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from the Wudao Liang Protection Station of the Kekexili Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration that the monitoring showed that the Tibetan antelopes that had previously migrated to the Zhuonai Lake area in the hinterland of Kekexili were gradually ending their calving and began to return to their original habitat with their young.
Surveillance footage near the Wudao Liang Protection Station shows that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led three Tibetan antelope cubs through the 3002 km of the Qinghai-Tibet Highway and the Wudao Liang North Bridge of the Qinghai-Tibet Railway. The Tibetan antelopes have begun to return.
According to expert analysis, in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope calves in the migratory flock accounts for one-fourth to one-fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope herds.
Lian Xinming, an associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Biological Research Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "At the beginning of the migration, the Tibetan antelope faces a high risk of predation, so the number of young in the herd will be relatively small, and there may even be no young."
According to the statistics of the Kekexili Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelopes returning is generally increasing year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelopes returning was 4,860, an increase of 338 over 2018.
Lian Xinming said: "It is expected that this year's Tibetan antelope migration will end in early September, and the number of returning Tibetan antelope is still expected to continue to increase."
The Tibetan antelope is a state-level protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from Sanjiangyuan in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet, and Arjinshan in Xinjiang go to Zhuo Nai Lake in the hinterland of Kekexili to give birth to lambs.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert on the protection of Tibetan antelopes in China and a researcher at the Shaanxi Provincial Institute of Zoology (Northwest Endangered Animal Research Institute), said: "Tibetan antelope migration is a process in which female Tibetan antelopes return to their habitat with their young after the end of calving. At first, the migration group leaving the calving ground is relatively large, but then Tibetan antelopes will return to their respective habitats according to different geographical populations and along different paths."
In order to ensure the safe return of the Tibetan antelope herd, the reporter learned that the Cocosiri Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration has arranged staff to continuously carry out video monitoring and patrol the jurisdiction in the main return area.
If it is found that a herd of Tibetan antelope is trying to cross the road, the patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time, so that the sheep can safely pass through the wildlife passage and ensure that they are as little as possible disturbed by humans on their way back.
So, how to relieve the heat in daily life?
Experts suggest that when going out in the summer, try to avoid the high-temperature period, and it is best not to walk or work in the hot sun before and after noon, because the sun is strongest during this time, and the possibility of heat stroke is higher.
If you must go out at this time, be sure to do a good job of protection, such as using a parasol, wearing a sun hat, wearing sunglasses, and applying sunscreen if possible to prevent sunburn.
As far as possible, choose light-colored, breathable cotton, linen and silk fabrics for clothes, and wear less chemical fiber clothing, so as not to lose heat in time when sweating a lot, causing heat stroke.
In hot and muggy weather, prepare enough water to drink, drink it in time, don't wait for thirst to drink water, because once you feel thirsty, your body is already short of water, each time you drink water, control it to 150 ml to 200 ml, drink warm water, don't drink ice water.
Depending on the temperature, general personnel drink 1.5 to 2 liters of water per day, and high-temperature workers drink 3 to 5 liters of water per day.
When sweating more, it is appropriate to add some salt water to make up for the salt lost by the body due to sweating.
In addition, the human body is prone to potassium deficiency in summer, which makes people feel tired and tired. Potassium-containing tea water is an excellent summer drink.
In summer, eat more fruits and vegetables with high water content, such as lettuce, cucumbers, tomatoes, etc.; fresh fruits, such as peaches, apricots, watermelons, melons and other water content of 80% to 90%, can be used to replenish water; dairy products can not only replenish water, but also meet the nutritional needs of the body.
In addition, people working in high-temperature environments should be properly supplemented with drinks containing elements such as potassium and magnesium.
In summer, the days are long and the nights are short, the temperature is high, the human metabolism is strong, the consumption is also large, and it is easy to feel tired.
Adequate sleep can relax the brain and body systems, which is not only conducive to work and study, but also a measure to prevent heat stroke.
According to experts, the best time to go to bed is between 22:00 and 23:00, and the best time to get up is between 5:30 and 6:30.
When sleeping, be careful not to lie under the air conditioning outlet and electric fan, so as not to suffer from air conditioning disease and heat injury.
Experts suggest that people who are engaged in outdoor activities or high-temperature operations can carry heat-preventing drugs such as ten drops of water, human Dan, musk zhengqi water or musk zhengqi pills, or place them in the nearest workplace and use them at any time to prevent heatstroke.
