APEC Trade Ministers Agree to Accelerate Regional Economic Recovery - Xinhua
Xinhua News Agency, Kuala Lumpur, July 25 (Reporter Lin Hao) The video conference of trade ministers of the members of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) was held on the 25th. The meeting pledged to work to reduce the impact of the new crown epidemic on the region's economy and accelerate the realization of a resilient, sustainable and inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was chaired by Malaysia, the host of this year's APEC Economic Leaders' Meeting.
A joint statement issued after the meeting said that APEC member trade ministers recognized the importance of a free, open, fair, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment to drive economic recovery at this challenging time.
The parties are committed to ensuring that the emergency measures taken in response to the epidemic are targeted, appropriate, transparent and temporary, and do not create unnecessary trade barriers and disrupt global supply chains, while adhering to World Trade Organization rules.
In the statement, APEC trade ministers pledged to strengthen cooperation to facilitate the flow of necessary goods and services, promote connectivity by strengthening supply chain resilience, and minimize disruptions to the flow of medical supplies, food and agricultural products to respond to the epidemic.
APEC trade ministers agreed on the need to discuss how to reduce non-tariff barriers that restrict trade in essential goods, and reaffirmed their commitment to facilitate the necessary cross-border movement of people without affecting the measures taken to stop the spread of the epidemic.
The meeting also issued a declaration on promoting the circulation of necessary commodities.
The declaration said that the economies will ensure that their trade measures taken in response to the epidemic are in line with WTO regulations, and pledged to take action in reducing non-tariff trade barriers and trade promotion to facilitate the flow of goods necessary under the epidemic.
Malaysia's Minister of International Trade and Industry Azmin Ali, who chaired the meeting, said that despite the impact of the epidemic, Malaysia is still committed to promoting the success of this year's APEC meeting, and the work of formulating APEC's post-2020 cooperation vision is progressing in an orderly manner.
Malaysia agreed to hold APEC-related meetings by video, but did not rule out the possibility of arranging a physical meeting at the end of the year when APEC leaders meet informally.
