Lin Huocan, reporter of Economic Daily and China Economic Net
In the first half of this year, in the face of the impact of the new crown pneumonia epidemic, China coordinated and promoted all aspects of epidemic prevention and control and economic and social development. The situation of epidemic prevention and control continued to improve, the steady recovery of the economy was obvious, and employment and price performance, which are closely related to people's livelihood, were generally stable. China's economy handed over a warm economic performance report card.
In the first two months of this year, the surveyed unemployment rate increased.
In particular, in February, the production and operation activities of many enterprises were basically suspended, the demand for labor by enterprises decreased, recruitment was delayed or canceled, and the urban survey unemployment rate increased.
With the gradual improvement of the epidemic prevention and control situation, the whole society's production and life order has been continuously restored.
The Party Central Committee adhered to the general tone of seeking progress while maintaining stability, further increased the hedging of macro policies, comprehensively strengthened the employment priority policy, and actively promoted the work of helping enterprises stabilize and expand employment.
China has increased its policy of hedging and stabilizing jobs, and has launched a policy combination of "reduction, exemption, delay and compensation," phased reduction and exemption of three social insurance unit contributions, allowing deferred payment of social insurance premiums, expanding the return of unemployment insurance for small and medium-sized micro-enterprises, benefiting from the work-training policy, and providing subsidies for enterprises to absorb key groups of employment, apprenticeship subsidies, etc.
With the implementation of various stable employment policies, the employment demand of enterprises has steadily rebounded, the employment situation has gradually improved, and the surveyed urban unemployment rate has gradually declined. In June, the surveyed unemployment rate was 5.7%.
Zhang Yi, director of the Department of Population and Employment Statistics of the National Bureau of Statistics, said that in the second quarter, various employment policies continued to be effective, and the labor force that had withdrawn in the previous period due to the impact of the epidemic gradually returned, and the urban labor participation rate in June increased by about 10 percentage points from February, close to the same period last year.
According to the data, the total urban employment in June increased by more than 19% compared with February, and most industries reached the pre-epidemic level; the average weekly working hours of employees in enterprises reached 46.8 hours, an increase of 6.6 hours from February and a slight increase of 0.1 hours from January.
Prices are also related to thousands of households.
In January this year, the CPI rose by 5.4% year-on-year, setting a new high for many years.
In February, although the year-on-year increase in CPI fell slightly, it was still in the "5 range."
The year-on-year increase in CPI is at a high level, which is driven by consumer demand before the Spring Festival, as well as the wrong month of the Spring Festival and the low year-on-year base.
However, the impact of the coronavirus epidemic on prices is particularly obvious.
Affected by the prevention and control of the epidemic, logistics delays, untimely supply of materials, and increased material transportation costs occurred throughout the country in January and February. In addition, some citizens hoarded and snapped up, and the prices of some necessities rose significantly.
In order to cope with the disturbance caused by the epidemic prevention and control to the price situation, the relevant departments have included important daily necessities in the scope of emergency transportation guarantee to ensure the smooth transportation of materials.
Under the effect of a series of policy measures, the market supply of vegetables and fruits has been effectively guaranteed.
In response to the rapid rise in pork prices at the beginning of this year, after the central government introduced the policy of ensuring supply and stabilizing prices, all regions and departments quickly implemented it, the supply of pork reserves was significantly improved, pig production capacity was restored in an orderly manner, and the production and marketing order gradually normalized.
Since March, pork prices have fallen continuously, and in May, the year-on-year increase in food prices fell to 10.6%; in June, pork prices rose slightly month-on-month due to factors such as a slowdown in the release of live pigs, a decrease in imports and a rebound in group consumption demand.
The seasonal variation of fresh vegetable prices is obvious, with an average increase of 3.4% in the first half of the year.
Affected by the higher comparison base in the same period last year, fresh fruit prices continued to decline year-on-year, with an average decline of 13.3% in the first half of the year.
The basic livelihood of the masses has been effectively safeguarded, and the overall economic and social situation has remained stable and orderly.
With the gradual recovery of transportation and logistics, localities have stepped up efforts to ensure supply, and market supply and demand conditions have improved.
Beginning in March, the CPI fell for four consecutive months, and the year-on-year increase also fell from 4.3% in March to 2.5% in June, and the price level generally returned to a stable level.
In the second half of the year, China's prices will continue to maintain a moderate level, with little overall inflationary pressure, but it is still necessary to promote the restoration of production and living order under the premise of normalizing epidemic prevention and control.
Effectively respond to natural disasters such as floods and droughts in the main production areas of grain, fruits and vegetables and other agricultural products, strengthen market supervision, and resolutely crack down on acts that disrupt market order such as hoarding and price gouging.
