Greenland opens a new round of mixed reform Shanghai's state-owned assets plan to transfer 17.5% of shares -Economic Observer-Professional financial news website
Economic Observer Network reporter Rao Xianjun On July 26, Greenland Holdings (600606.SH) issued a "prompt announcement on the state-owned shareholders' intention to transfer part of the company's shares and resumption of trading through public solicitation of transferees."
The content of the announcement shows that in order to further deepen the reform of state-owned state-owned enterprises, optimize the restructuring of the layout of state-owned assets, and improve the shareholding structure of Greenland, Shanghai Real Estate (Group) Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as "Shanghai Real Estate") and Shanghai City Investment (Group) Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as "Shanghai City Investment") intend to transfer part of the shares held by the company through public solicitation of transferees. The total proportion of shares to be transferred does not exceed 17.5% of Greenland's total share capital.
The price of the shares to be transferred is not lower than the higher of the following: the arithmetic average of the daily weighted average price of the 30 trading days prior to the indicative announcement date (July 27, 2020); and the audited net asset value per share of the company in the most recent fiscal year.
At present, there is still no conclusion on the new strategic investor of Greenland. According to the information released in the announcement, it is estimated that the new strategic investor needs to pay about 14 billion yuan to win the 17.5% equity transferred in the mixed reform of Greenland.
It is worth noting that after the completion of the transfer of shares, it is expected that Greenland still has no controlling shareholder and actual controller, but the control structure may change significantly.
Since its establishment, Greenland Holdings has carried out a number of institutional reforms: from 1992 to 1997, it operated in accordance with market-oriented rules under a purely state-owned system; from 1997 to 2013, it established and continuously improved the shareholding system of state-owned holding and employee shareholding; from 2013 to 2015, it introduced strategic investors to form a mixed ownership system of cross-shareholding and mutual integration of state-owned and non-public capital; from 2015 to the present, it has been listed as a public company.
Greenland's current mixed reform plan is similar to Gree. In December 2019, Zhuhai Alum, led by Gaolu Capital, took over a 15% stake in Gree Electric (000651.SZ) for 41.662 billion yuan, and Gree Group retreated to a small shareholder. After completing the mixed reform, Gree Electric implemented a modern corporate management method such as executive incentive plan and no actual controller structure.
Zhang Yuliang, chairman and president of Greenland Holdings, said that Greenland's move is an important measure for Shanghai to promote the comprehensive reform of state-owned state-owned enterprises and accelerate the reform of state-owned state-owned enterprises in a new stage in accordance with the requirements of the Party Central Committee. It fully demonstrates the new idea of reform tailored to local conditions and tailor-made. By introducing new outstanding strategic shareholders to listed companies, it supports enterprises to further improve the degree of marketization, enhance the freedom of operation and management, and accelerate the full release of reform vitality.
