Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to sue the school after being compensated for being smashed while playing in the university playground?
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed, and the children sued the school after receiving compensation.
□ Zhao Yifan, Correspondent
Three-year-old Xiao Wen was playing in a university playground when he was accidentally hit in the head by Chen Mou of the softball team while throwing a ball.
After Chen's compensation, Xiaowen's father, Mr. Wen, as Xiaowen's legal representative, sued the school to the court, demanding that the school where the playground was located apologize and pay a total of 20,000 yuan for medical expenses and emotional damages.
Recently, after the trial of this case, the Haidian District People's Court of Beijing held that the school had set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, had fulfilled the appropriate safety and security obligations, and Chen had made compensation, according to which the plaintiff's lawsuit was dismissed.
Mr. Wen complained that during the summer vacation in 2019, he took Xiao Wen to play in the school playground, when the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid the resulting risks, Xiao Wen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents were in the safe area designated by the softball team.
But then Chen Mou, a member of the softball team, lost his hand while throwing the ball, causing the softball to fly over the protective net to the above-mentioned safe area and hit the back of Xiao Wen's head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believes that the facilities of the school stadium do not meet the relevant safety regulations and do not effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The school's negligence led to the above incident, which caused Xiao Wen to suffer great physical and mental pain, and also brought great pain to his family, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In response, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net in the playground, and posted management regulations and training notices, informing that access to the playground must be kept at a safe distance from the training site and reminding them of their own safety. The plaintiff could not prove that the school "failed to fulfill its security obligations," so it did not agree to compensation.
After the trial, the court held that the site of the incident was a site open to the public free of charge by the university involved, and although the school had a security obligation for the management of the playground, such a security obligation only needed to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net in the playground, and has fulfilled the appropriate safety and security obligations, and Chen also compensated Xiaowen for more than 2,000 yuan in medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses in accordance with the compensation agreement previously reached. The two sides agreed to resolve the dispute once.
After the incident, Xiaowen's parents again claimed compensation from the school, which was groundless, and the court dismissed all the plaintiff's claims.
After the verdict, neither side appealed, and the sentence is now in effect.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, the school, as the manager of the public place, has the obligation of safety and security; in the case that the third party's behavior causes damage to others, the third party bears the tort liability, and the public place manager who has not fulfilled the obligation of safety and security shall bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
The judge said that as the manager of the public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the whole place, foresee the possible danger and damage, so that he is most likely to take the necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of loss or mitigate the extent of damage, and the cost of avoiding and mitigating the occurrence of damage is the lowest, so the law stipulates that he bears the corresponding guarantee obligation to engage in social activities.
In this case, for the unspecified group of people entering the playground, which is open to the public free of charge, the safety and security obligations of the school should be commensurate with the social activities it is engaged in. Specifically, it is mainly necessary to take basic safety measures and have an obligation to inform about hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive security obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has taken measures to set up protective nets and fulfill its obligation to inform, it can be concluded that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for third-party infringement, even if the managers of public places such as schools fail to fulfill their security obligations, their liability is also a supplement to damages. According to the newly promulgated Civil Code, after the managers assume additional liability, they can also recover from the third party.
Therefore, in such accidents, victims should not expand the scope of claims after they have already received compensation from the direct infringer.
