Beijing News (Reporter Liu Zhen) On July 26, the Beijing Philharmonic Choir issued an obituary. Yang Hongnian, the founder of the Beijing Philharmonic Choir, a famous Chinese conductor and music educator, a life-long academic member of the Central Conservatory of Music, and a professor of the Department of Conducting, died at 13:55 on July 26, 2020 in Beijing. He was 86 years old.
Photo from the official website of the Beijing Philharmonic Choir.
Yang Hongnian was born in 1934, a native of Nanjing, Jiangsu Province, and loved music since childhood.
In 1951, he served as the conductor of the chorus of Nanjing People's Radio Station. In the fall of 1951, he was admitted to the music department of East China Normal University in Shanghai. He studied conducting with Professor Yang Jiaren and German conductor Hizmann, and studied composition and polyphony with former Soviet expert Arzamanov.
In 1958, he taught at the music department of the Beijing Art Teachers College, and in 1973, he was transferred to the composition and conducting departments of the Central Conservatory of Music.
Yang Hongnian founded the Beijing Philharmonic Choir in 1983.
For more than 30 years, adhering to the tenet of "love and dedication," he has led this choir to sing all over the world and won dozens of awards in important competitions at home and abroad.
He has conducted the performances of more than 30 groups such as the Central Orchestra Chorus, the Central National Song and Dance Troupe, the Oriental Song and Dance Troupe, and the Shanghai Chorus, and held many symphony concerts and choral concerts.
He is the author of "Band Training," "Chorus Training," "Two Song Writing," "Children's Song Collection" (upper and lower volumes) and the paper "On the Problem of Choral Pitch," "On the Acoustic Hierarchy of Orchestral Music," as well as the translation of "Choral Instrumentation" and "Debussy's Harmony Language."
