Israel to strengthen prevention and control of repeated epidemics
2020-07-26 04:56:44 Source: Guangming Daily Author: Wang Sisuo Editor: Wang Sisuo
Israel steps up prevention and control of repeated outbreaks
At the beginning of the outbreak, Israel's prevention and control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of new coronavirus pneumonia in Israel has recently increased significantly. The Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of new coronavirus pneumonia was confirmed in Israel, prompting the closure of all entry and exit ports, the suspension of non-essential industries, the conversion of schools to online teaching, the restriction of public transportation and non-essential social activities, the lockdown of cities with serious epidemics, and the joint maintenance of prevention and control measures by the military and police.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results, and by mid-May, the number of new confirmed cases of new coronavirus pneumonia in Israel had fallen to single digits.
With the epidemic under control, Israel's prevention and control measures have been fully lifted, and since June, the number of new confirmed cases of new coronavirus has gradually rebounded.
Especially since July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, the daily number of new cases in Israel has been more than 1,500 for eight days, and as of the time of publication on July 25, there were 916 new cases on the same day.
As of July 25, Israel had 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths.
In the face of the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gyms, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other public entertainment venues, and introduced a policy of restricting public transport, stipulating that no more than 20 passengers per bus.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of "city closure" on weekends, stipulating the implementation of "city closure" from 17:00 every Friday to 5:00 every Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but shops, shopping centers, hairdressers, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while supermarkets, pharmacies and other basic services will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited on all dates and times, gyms, studios and other places will be closed, and restaurants and cafes are prohibited from serving food, and only take-out services are allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli public did not pay enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and failed to form a joint effort with the government in combating the epidemic.
After the recurrence of the epidemic in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest because the government's prevention and control measures affected their own economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people held a demonstration in Tel Aviv, arguing that the anti-epidemic policy affects the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's official residence in Jerusalem to protest Prime Minister Netanyahu's ban on restaurants, cafes and other prevention and control measures without corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people do not comply with the rules of wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters when they are outdoors. In order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing a mask, many people only wear a mask on their chin or hang it on their wrist.
During the recurrence of the epidemic, schools are the hardest hit areas for the spread of the new coronavirus, and according to the reporter's recent visit to this kindergarten, the teachers and students of the kindergarten did not wear masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other, laying a hidden danger for a large number of teachers and students to be infected with the virus.
Professor Eli Waksman, a member of the Israeli National Security Council's expert advisory group on combating the epidemic, believes that Israel is heading towards a "dangerous situation," pointing out that the current epidemic prevention and control measures taken by Israel are not enough, and all leisure and recreational activities and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to combat the epidemic, and the parliament and government departments should abandon their respective interests as soon as possible, reach an agreement on the issue of combating the epidemic, and formulate clear steps that include relevant restrictions in different sectors.
