Membrane separation technology helps to crack the "greenhouse effect"
Membrane separation technology helps crack the "greenhouse effect"
Schematic diagram of the new hybrid matrix membrane preparation technology
Our reporter Shang Rui reports: Recently, the atmospheric environment and bioenergy team of Tianjin University has made great progress in the "membrane separation method to capture carbon dioxide" and successfully developed a new hybrid matrix membrane preparation technology, which greatly improves the carbon dioxide capture performance of membrane materials.
The related results have been published as the cover article of the international journal Greenhouse Gases: Science and Technology.
The "greenhouse effect" is a major environmental problem plaguing human development, and carbon dioxide emissions are responsible for the "greenhouse effect."
How to efficiently capture and use the carbon dioxide emitted by humans is the focus of scientists.
"Membrane separation method" is an emerging carbon dioxide capture technology, which separates carbon dioxide gas with the help of membrane material, and has the characteristics of high efficiency, energy saving and simple operation.
How to let the membrane material "breathe deeply" and improve the gas separation efficiency is the bottleneck difficulty of using membrane separation to capture carbon dioxide.
Tianjin University research team innovative ideas, through repeated experiments, to explore the impact of different solvents on membrane gas separation performance.
The experimental results show that with N-methylpyrrolidone as the preparation solvent, the distribution of carbon nanotubes in the generated membrane material is more uniform and "more breathable," which effectively enhances the gas separation efficiency and rate of the membrane material.
The carbon dioxide separation performance of the hybrid matrix membrane prepared by this new technology is close to the theoretical separation limit of such membrane materials at present.
"The new technology provides new ideas for the capture of carbon dioxide by membrane separation."
Li Run, a member of the atmospheric environment and bioenergy team at Tianjin University, said: "We hope that this technology can provide strong support for the treatment of flue gas in coal-fired power plants and chemical companies in the future, and play a major role in controlling greenhouse gas emissions."
